@Node "Introduction" "AFileEnglish.guide/Introduction"
@Next "Installation"
@Prev "Main"
@Toc "Main"

Introduction
************

   AFile is a data file manager, that is a tool which lets you create
and manager your files (addresses, video collections, clients, etc...)
using an Intuition interface.  There is not limitation to the number of
fields or records. The program offerts the standard printing, sorting,
and data importing/exporting functions.

   AFile uses AREXX as it's programming language. You can create full
input masks with background picture, field positionning, checking of
entered data, menus and printing customization.

   Criticisms and suggestions will always be welcomed. Write to:

                           M. GOUNELLE Denis

                         27, rue Jules GUESDE

                       45400 FLEURY-LES-AUBRAIS

                                FRANCE

                   EMail: denis.gounelle@wanadoo.fr

     Homepage: http://perso.wanadoo.fr/denis.gounelle/index_e.html

   Thanks to Yves PERRENOUD for it's numerous suggestions.


@EndNode

@Node "Installation" "AFileEnglish.guide/Installation"
@Next "Startup"
@Prev "Introduction"
@Toc "Main"

Installation
************

   Since v4.00, AFile requires V36 of greater of the Kickstart. AFile
also needs the @{b}mathieedoubbas.library@{ub} which is provided on system disks.

   AFile is now localized, so it can adapt itself to your favorite
language.  All you have to do is to copy the good catalog file into the
directory corresponding to your language. For exemple, if your default
language is french, copy the @{b}francais.catalog@{ub} file into the
@{b}SYS:Locale/Catalogs/Francais@{ub} directory, under the @{b}AFile.catalog@{ub} name.


@EndNode

@Node "Startup" "AFileEnglish.guide/Startup"
@Next "MenuPrinc"
@Prev "Installation"
@Toc "Main"

Startup
*******

   The program can be started both from CLI and Workbench. In both
cases, you can specify a file to use, with the usual method, so the
program will jump directly to the visualisation/modification window.

   The following arguments may also be specified:

@{i}NOCASE@{ui}
     asks search and sort operations to be case independant by default
     (using interface only)

@{i}PRINTSCRIPT <script's name>@{ui}
@{i}PRINTSCRIPT=<script's name>@{ui}
     specifies the name of the AREXX script to use to print records,
     instead of the builtin method.

     The script will be called for each record to print, with record
     data directly accessible using the @{i}GETFIELD@{ui} command. The standard
     output is automatically redirected to the printer, so you just
     have to use the "SAY" command to output data. See @{"AREXX Interface" Link "AREXX"}.

     You can also specify a printing script in input masks. See
     @{"Input masks" Link "InputMask"}.

@{i}INPUTMASK <mask's name>@{ui}
@{i}INPUTMASK=<mask's name>@{ui}
     specifies an input mask at startup. This is usefull mostly when a
     file name is also specified.

@{i}AREXXWIN <window specification>@{ui}
@{i}AREXXWIN=<window specification>@{ui}
     specifies the output window for AREXX scripts started from AFile.
     By default, AFile opens a window which covers all the screen,
     except the menu bar.

@{i}FONT <name>@{ui}
@{i}FONT=<name>@{ui}
     specifies the font to use, rather than the default text font. The
     font name must be in the <font name><Y size> format (e.g.
     "courier9"). AFile can't use a proportional font.

@{i}PUBSCREEN <name of a public screen>@{ui}
@{i}PUBSCREEN=<name of a public screen>@{ui}
     specifies the name of the public screen to use. By default, AFile
     uses the Worbench's screen.

@{i}SCREENMODE <mode name>@{ui}
@{i}SCREENMODE=<mode name>@{ui}
     specifies both that AFile must use a custom screen, and the screen
     mode asked for this screen (for example: "PAL: Hires"). The
     specified mode name must exactly match the name in the mode
     requester of the Preferences @{b}ScreenMode@{ub} program.

     If both SCREENMODE and DISPLAYID arguments are specified, the
     SCREENMODE argument is taken first. If the given mode does not
     exist, then AFile will use the DISPLAYID argument.

@{i}DISPLAYID <mode identifieur>@{ui}
@{i}DISPLAYID=<mode identifieur>@{ui}
     specifies both that AFile must use a custom screen, and the screen
     mode asked for this screen (for example 0x29004 for "PAL: Hires
     lace"). This is saffer than the SCREENMODE argument, because
     screen mode names depend upon the language set in the Preferences.

     If the given mode does not exist, AFile will use the Worbench
     screen.

@{i}DEPTH <number of planes>@{ui}
@{i}DEPTH=<number of planes>@{ui}
     specifies both that AFile must use a custom screen, and the number
     of planes asked for this screen. This is usefull when an input
     mask loads a background picture, and you want to be sure to have
     the right number of colors.

     If neither SCREENMODE nor DISPLAYID are specified, AFile will use
     a Hires screen of 640x256 or 640x200 pixels.


@EndNode

@Node "MenuPrinc" "AFileEnglish.guide/MenuPrinc"
@Next "DefStruct"
@Prev "Startup"
@Toc "Main"

Main menu
*********

   This menu appears when the program is started, if you didn't
specified a file name as an argument. This menu has the following items:

@{i}New file@{ui}
     Allows to create a new file. A file requester will allow you to
     specify the name of the file to create. See @{"Structure definition" Link "DefStruct"}.

@{i}Modify structure@{ui}
     Allows to modify the structure of an existing file. A file
     requester will allow you to select the file to modify. See
     @{"Structure modification" Link "ModStruct"}.

@{i}Open file@{ui}
     Allows to open an existing file. A file requester will allow you
     to select the file to open, then the visualisation/modification
     window will appear. See @{"Data access" Link "DataAccess"}.

@{i}Quit@{ui}
     Terminates AFile execution.


@EndNode

@Node "DefStruct" "AFileEnglish.guide/DefStruct"
@Next "ModStruct"
@Prev "MenuPrinc"
@Toc "Main"

Structure definition
********************

   AFile handles files made of fixed length records. All the records
have the same structure, made of an unlimited number of fields. Each
field is defined by it's name, size and type. The number of records in
a file is limited only by the capacity of your hard disk.

   Field's name can't be longer than 32 characters, and may contain any
character.  However, you shouldn't use spaces if you think you will use
AREXX to access to the file. Of course, each field's name must be
unique.

   Field's size is limited to 65535 bytes, except for "DATE", "ENUM"
and "BOOLEAN" fields, which are 8, 1 and 1 bytes long, respectively.
For numeric fields, you can also specify the number of digits after the
decimal point. Possible field's types are:

@{i}alpha@{ui}
     alphabetic value only (lowercase and upercase letters, space,
     dash, single quote)

@{i}numeric@{ui}
     numeric value (real or integer)

@{i}alphanum@{ui}
     any value

@{i}date@{ui}
     date (day, month, year with century)

@{i}boolean@{ui}
     boolean value (TRUE or FALSE)

@{i}enum@{ui}
     value contained in a list specified when defining the file

   The definition structure requester is made of a display area, where
are displayed the field's definitions (name/type/length). You can use
the scroller to scroll the display. The current field is displayed
under a blue background. To select a field, you just have to click upon
it's definition: it will automatically copied in the gadgets.

   The gadget row at the bottom of the window allow the following
operations:

@{i}Add@{ui}
     adds a new field as the last field

@{i}Replace@{ui}
     replaces the current field. This allow (for example) to modify the
     name, size or type of a field.

@{i}Insert@{ui}
     inserts a new field before the current field

@{i}Remove@{ui}
     removes the current field

   To define a new field, you'll have to enter it's name and length in
corresponding string gadgets, and to select it's type using the @{i}Type@{ui}
cycle gadget. If the field's type is "ENUM", you will also have to
enter the list of possible values (separated by commas) in the @{i}Values@{ui}
gadget. Then you must click upon the @{i}Add@{ui} gadget: the new field will be
added to the list, and selected as the current field. If the field
can't be added (no memory, name not unique, etc...) the screen will
flash.

   The definition requester also has a menu, with the following
commands:

@{i}Copy structure@{ui}
     Copies the structure of an existing file. Note that the structure
     currently displayed in the requester will be lost ! A file
     requester will appear, so you can select the file which structure
     is to be copied.

@{i}Print structure@{ui}
     Prints the file's structure, that is the definition of all the
     fields. You can print the structure to the printer, or the a file.

@{i}Abort@{ui}
     Cancels structure definition, and go back to main window without
     creating the file.

@{i}Save@{ui}
     Records structure definition, and go back to main window after
     creating the file.

@{i}Encrypt data@{ui}
     Data in the file will be encryted, using a password that you will
     have to provide when you record structure definition. This
     password will be asked for each time the user will try to access
     to the data.

     @{i}Caution ! If you ever forget this passord, you will never be able
     to access to the data in the file !@{ui}


@EndNode

@Node "ModStruct" "AFileEnglish.guide/ModStruct"
@Next "DataAccess"
@Prev "DefStruct"
@Toc "Main"

Structure modification
**********************

   This allows you to modify the structure of an existing file: you can
add some fields, remove some others (however, you can't delete all the
fields), modify a field's length, etc... You can also change a field
type, but use this function with care : if the new file type is not
"ALPHANUM", data in this field will be list.

   The modification requester is quite the same as the definition
requester (see @{"Structure Definition" Link "DefStruct"}). The only difference is that the
@{i}Copy structure@{ui} menu item is disabled.

   Once the structure has been modified, use the @{i}Save@{ui} menu item to
record your changes: AFile will automatically convert the file into the
new structure. Take care that deleted records will be lost during this
operation, and that this convertion may fail if there is not enough
free space on the volume where is the file.

   If some data will be lost during the convertion (shorter or removed
fields, deleted records, etc...), you will be asked to confirm the
operation.

   With the @{i}Options@{ui} menu, you can remove or add data encryption. If the
encryption option is enabled when you record the new structure, AFile
will ask you to enter a password. This can also be used to change the
password for a file: you just have to ask to modify the structure of
this file, record the structure without any change, and enter the new
password.


@EndNode

@Node "DataAccess" "AFileEnglish.guide/DataAccess"
@Prev "ModStruct"
@Toc "Main"

Data access
***********

   The visualisation/modification window is made of a display area
where data is displayed, of a status line and of a row of gadgets.

   The gadgets showing the data are the same width as the corresponding
field, except if the screen is not large enough. Each time you modify
the value of a field, AFile will check that this new value is
compatible with the field's type.

   Dates must be entered in the "DD/MM/YYYY" format (with century) or
just "DD/MM/YY" (the current century will be added automatically).
Entering "?" is an easy way to specify today's date (see @{"Aliases" Link "Alias"}). This
shortcut may be used anywhere a date is to be entered (search
requester, etc...).

   The first status line shows the type and size of the current field.
The second line shows the file's name, and current position in the file
under the X/Y form, where X is the current record number and Y the last
record number. When a sort has been activated, the @{i}(Sorted)@{ui} word is
displayed after the file's name. If the current record has been
modfied, the @{i}Modified@{ui} word is displayed at the right of the status line.

   The row of gadgets allows the following operations (from left to
right):

   - go to the first record

   - go to the previous record

   - write the current record

   - go to the next record

   - go to the last record

   - go to a specifed record (1)

   - delete the current record

   - print n records starting from the current record (1)

   - previous fields page

   - next fields page

   (1) See @{"Number request" Link "ReqNombre"}

   If the current record has been modified, the changes will
automatically be written if you move to another record. When you are on
the last record, asking to go to the next record will automatically
create a new record.

   All other operations may be started with menus.


 @{" File    " Link "FileMenu"}              The File menu
 @{" Edit    " Link "EditMenu"}              The Edit menu
 @{" Special " Link "SpecialMenu"}              The Special menu


@EndNode

@Node "FileMenu" "AFileEnglish.guide/FileMenu"
@Next "EditMenu"
@Prev "DataAccess"
@Toc "DataAccess"

The file menu
=============

@{i}Undelete@{ui}
     From AFile's point of vue, deleting a record just mean setting a
     flag for this record, which tells this record is deleted and must
     not be accessed. The record is not actually removed: data is still
     here. The menu item allows you to clear all deletion flags, so the
     corresponding records may be accessed again.

@{i}Pack file@{ui}
     Actually removes deleted record (you will be asked for
     confirmation). After this, you won't be able to undelete these
     records, but the file will be smaller because the data for these
     records will be definitly removed. Take care that this operation
     may fail if there is not enough free space on the volume where is
     the file.

@{i}Informations@{ui}
     Displays some informations about the current file: name, number of
     fields, record size, number of available records, number of
     deleted records.

@{i}Print structure@{ui}
     Prints the file's structure, that is the definition of all the
     fields. You can print the structure to the printer, or the a file.

@{i}About...@{ui}
     Displays some informations about AFile, like the current DISPLAYID
     and SCREENMODE.

@{i}Close file@{ui}
     Close the current file, and go back to main window.

@{i}Close and quit@{ui}
     Close the current file, and terminates the program.


@EndNode

@Node "EditMenu" "AFileEnglish.guide/EditMenu"
@Next "SpecialMenu"
@Prev "FileMenu"
@Toc "DataAccess"

The Edit menu
=============

@{i}Cancel changes@{ui}
     Reads the current record from the file, so cancels all changes
     since last write.

@{i}Select mask@{ui}
     Selects an input mask. A file requester will appear, so you can
     specify the mask to load. See @{"Input masks" Link "InputMask"}.

@{i}Forget mask@{ui}
     Forgets the current input mask.

@{i}Search@{ui}
     Searches a record with a given value in a specified field. A field
     request will appear, so you can specify which field the value is
     to be searched in. Then you will have to enter the value to
     search, and search options:

    @{i}Exact@{ui}
          Searches for a field which is equal to the value (option
          set), or just containing the value (option cleared). This
          option is available only for "ALPHA" and "ALPHANUM" fields,
          and when a "equal" or "not equal" comparison is asked.

    @{i}min = MAJ@{ui}
          Case independant (option set) or dependant (option cleared)
          search (only available for "ALPHA" and "ALPHANUM" fields).

    @{i}Comparison@{ui}
          Allow searching of a equal, different, lower, upper, etc...
          value.

@{i}Seach next@{ui}
     Continues searching, starting from next record.


@EndNode

@Node "SpecialMenu" "AFileEnglish.guide/SpecialMenu"
@Next "ImportExport"
@Prev "EditMenu"
@Toc "DataAccess"

The Special menu
================

@{i}Add sort key@{ui}
     Add a sort key on a specified field. A first requester will appear
     so you can specify the field which is to be used for sorting. A
     second requester will allow you to specify sort parameters:
     increasing/decreasing order, case dependant/independant.  Once the
     sorting done, AFile will display the first record in the sorting
     order. Then all your moves withing the records
     (first/previous/next/last) will be made in the sorting order.

     Take care that AFile only does a "logical" sort: the order of the
     records within the file is not actually modified. Sorting a file
     may use a lot of memory if the file contains a lot of records. As
     long as the sort is activated, you won't be able to add or remove
     records, to modified a value in the field which is used for
     sorting, and to use the @{i}Undelete@{ui} or @{i}Pack file@{ui} menu items.

@{i}Remove sort key@{ui}
     Removes the last, or all sort keys. Once all the sort keys have
     been removed, you will be able to add or remove records, and the
     moves within the file will use the "physical" order of the records
     in the file.

@{i}Reorder records@{ui}
     This actually modifies the order of the records in the file (you
     will be asked for confirmation). Take care that this operation may
     fail if there is not enough free space on the volume where is the
     file, and that all deleted records will be definitly lost.

@{i}Import@{ui}
     Imports data from an ASCII file. The new records will be appended
     to the end of the file. See @{"Importing/Exporting data" Link "ImportExport"}.

@{i}Export@{ui}
     Exports data to an ASCII file. All the records will be exported.
     See @{"Importing/Exporting data" Link "ImportExport"}.

@{i}Execute script@{ui}
     Allows to run an AREXX script. A file requester will allow you to
     select the script to run. See @{"AREXX Interface" Link "AREXX"}.


@EndNode

@Node "ImportExport" "AFileEnglish.guide/ImportExport"
@Next "ReqNombre"
@Prev "SpecialMenu"
@Toc "Main"

Importing/Exporting data
************************

   Selecting the @{i}Import@{ui} (or @{i}Export@{ui}) item brings up a requester, which
allows you to enter all the required parameters to import (or export)
data.

   The first parameter is the name of the source (or target) ASCII file.

   Then you will have to specify the field delimiter and record
delimiter characters. These delimiters may be entered as a single
character (i.e. ";") or as an ASCII decimal code (i.e. "\\010" for a
new line character). If you want to use an ASCII decimal code, it must
be preceded by a backslash character ("\\"). If you want to use a "\\"
as a delimiter, you just have to type it twice : "\\\\".

   Last, you will have to select the fields to transfert. The
left-handed list shows the names of all the defined fields. The
right-handed list shows the names of the fields to transfert.  To copy
a field from one list to the other, you just have to click on it's
name. The request has a menu, which "All" and "None" items allow to
select or unselect all the fields.

   The fields will be transfered in the given order. You can specify a
same field several time in the transfert list. When importing data, the
special "<Ignore>" field allow to skip a column in the input file.

   Note that the request has a menu, which "Save" and "Load" items
allow to save and load all the import/export options.


@EndNode

@Node "ReqNombre" "AFileEnglish.guide/ReqNombre"
@Next "InputMask"
@Prev "ImportExport"
@Toc "Main"

Number request
**************

   The number request can be controled with the keyboard. The "+" and
"-" keys increment and decrement the current value by one. As any other
request, the "RETURN" and "ESCAPE" keys respectively validate and
cancel the request.

   You can also enter a number with the keyboard. For example, if you
press the "5" key, the request will show the digit "5". Then, if you
press the "2" key, the request will jump to the number "52". You can
use the "BACKSPACE" key to go back from one digit (in our example, to
go back to the digit "5"). Last, the "DEL" key erases the number. The
request will then show the digit "1".


@EndNode

@Node "InputMask" "AFileEnglish.guide/InputMask"
@Next "MsgSpec"
@Prev "ImportExport"
@Toc "Main"

Input masks
***********

   Input masks allow to do a lot of things: customize data display,
menus and printing, help the user when he (or she) is entering data,
check the data he (or she) has entered.

   From AFile's point of vue, a mask is an AREXX script with comments
in a special format.  The general form of this script is like follows:

     /*
      * Sample input mask for AFile
      *
      * $MSG
      *      <message specification>
      * $END
      *
      * $MASK <background picture>
      *      <mask specification>
      * $END
      *
      * $MENU
      *      <menu specification>
      * $END
      *
      * $PRINT <print script>
      *
      * $PRINTFMT <print format string>
      */
     
     PARSE ARG field value
     
     <AREXX intructions>
     
     EXIT 0

   You don't have to enter all the specifications: an input mask can
only have a single $MSG specification (for example). Within a
specification, you may also enter comments:

     /* $MSG
      *      specification line
      **     comment line (begins whith " **")
      *      specification line
      * $END
      */

   To select an input mask, you have to use the "Select mask" menu
item. To cancel the mask, use the "Forget mask" item. See @{"The Edit menu" Link "EditMenu"}.

   You may also associate an input mask to a data file, so it will
automatically be loaded each time the data file is opened. In order to
use this possibility, the input mask file's name must be equal to the
name of the data file, followed by the @{b}.mask@{ub} suffix. For example, if
you want to define an input mask for a data file named @{b}Addresses@{ub}, it's
name must be @{b}Addresses.mask@{ub}. The two files must be in the same
directory.


 @{" $MSG      " Link "MsgSpec"}               : Message specification
 @{" $MASK     " Link "MaskSpec"}               : Mask specification
 @{" $MENU     " Link "MenuSpec"}               : Menu specification
 @{" $PRINT    " Link "PrintSpec"}               : Print script specification
 @{" $PRINTFMT " Link "PrintFmtSpec"}               : Print format specification


@EndNode

@Node "MsgSpec" "AFileEnglish.guide/MsgSpec"
@Next "MaskSpec"
@Prev "InputMask"
@Toc "InputMask"

$MSG specification
==================

   The specification lines must contains:

  1. a field's name

  2. a flag telling if the verification script is to call

  3. a message

   Here is an example:

     /* $MSG
      **     Field's name    Verify?         Message
      *      NUMBER          -               Product number
      *      QUANTITY        CHECK           Quantity supplied
      *      SUPPLIER        -               Supplier's name
      *      SUPPLY_DATE     CHECK           Date of supply
      * $END
      */

   The message is displayed above the status line when the
corresponding field is selected.  If the "CHECK" keyword is present in
column two, the AREXX script which contains the input mask is called
each time the value of the field is modified, with the field's name and
the new value as arguments. The script must return a 0 return code if
the value is accepted, or a non-0 return code if the value is refused.
Date values will be supplied in the "AAAAMMDD" format, and boolean
values will be either "T" or "F".

   The script cannot use the SEEK, WRITE, APPEND, DELETE, SEARCH, SORT,
RELEASE, REORDER, PACK, UNDELETE, SETFIELD, and CLOSE commands on the
current file. See @{"AREXX Interface" Link "AREXX"}.


@EndNode

@Node "MaskSpec" "AFileEnglish.guide/MaskSpec"
@Next "MenuSpec"
@Prev "MsgSpec"
@Toc "InputMask"

$MASK specification
===================

   This specification is more powerfull than the $MSG specification,
because it allows to load a background picture, and to set the position
of the fields on the window. The specification lines must contains:

  1. a field's name

  2. the left offset (X position, in pixels)

  3. the top offset (Y position, in pixels)

  4. the field width (in pixels)

  5. a flag telling if the verification script is to call

  6. a message

   Here is an example:

      * $MASK        Work:Pictures/AFile/Address.pic
      **     Field's name    XPos    YPos    Width   AREXX?  Message
      *      NUMBER          400     4       -       -       Customer's number
      *      FIRSTNAME       400     26      100     -       Customer's first name
      *      NAME            400     48      100     -       Customer's name
      * $END
      */

   The (optional) file's name after the $MASK word must correspond to a
picture file, in the standard IFF format. This picture will be loaded
as the background picture, while the input mask is loaded. The
picture's palette will be loaded too. Note that HAM and HAM8 pictures
are not supported by AFile.

   AFile is able to load a picture which is not in the same resolution
that the screen used. You may use the DEPTH argument to specify a
number of colors (see @{"Startup" Link "Startup"}).

   The X and Y positions, and the width, are used to display the fields
on the window.  If you specify "-" for the width, the default field's
width is used.

   The message is displayed above the status line when the
corresponding field is selected.  If the "CHECK" keyword is present in
column two, the AREXX script which contains the input mask is called
each time the value of the field is modified (see @{"$MSG Specification" Link "MsgSpec"}).


@EndNode

@Node "MenuSpec" "AFileEnglish.guide/MenuSpec"
@Next "PrintSpec"
@Prev "MaskSpec"
@Toc "InputMask"

$MENU specification
===================

   The specification lines must contains:

  1. the menu item's title

  2. a flag telling if arguments are needed

  3. the name of the AREXX script to run

   Here is an example:

     /* $MENU
      **     Item's name     Arguments?      Script's name
      *      Weekly stats    -               Work:Lib/Stats.rexx
      *      Daily extract   ARGS,QUIET      Work:Lib/Extract.rexx
      * $END
      */

   The items will be added in a new menu: the @{i}Extras@{ui} menu. The first
ten items will have a keyboard shortcut. Each time an item will be
selected, AFile will call the corresponding AREXX script, after having
eventually asked some arguments (in the case the "ARGS" keyword is
present in column two), and without output window if the "QUIET"
keyword is present in column two.


@EndNode

@Node "PrintSpec" "AFileEnglish.guide/PrintSpec"
@Next "PrintFmtSpec"
@Prev "MenuSpec"
@Toc "InputMask"

$PRINT specification
====================

   The $PRINT word must be followed by the name of the AREXX script to
call to print records.

   The script will be called each time a record is to print, with the
fields of this record directly accessible using the @{i}GETFIELD@{ui} AREXX
command. The output will be redirected to the printer, so you will just
have to use "SAY" command to send data.  See @{"AREXX Interface" Link "AREXX"}.

   This specification overwrites the optional PRINTSCRIPT argument (see
@{"Startup" Link "Startup"}), as long as the input mask is loaded. Any $PRINTFMT
specification before a $PRINT specification will be ignored.


@EndNode

@Node "PrintFmtSpec" "AFileEnglish.guide/PrintFmtSpec"
@Next "Alias"
@Prev "PrintSpec"
@Toc "InputMask"

$PRINTFMT specification
=======================

   The $PRINTFMT keyword must be followed by a format string, showing
how to print records.  For each record to print, data will be formated
using this string, before being sent to the printer.

   The format string can contain the following specifications :

%num[:{l|c|r}[size]]
     Replaced by the value of the "num"-th field, eventually left
     justified (l), centered (c) or right justified (r) on "size"
     positions. If "size" is omitted, the field's size is used.
     Examples : %3 %2:r %11:c20

$no[:{l|c|r}[taille]]
     Replaced by the name of the "num"-th field, eventually left
     justified (l), centered (c) or right justified (r) on "size"
     positions. If "size" is omitted, the field's size is used.

\\n
     Replaced by a line-feed character

\\f
     Replaced by a form-feed character

\\char
     Replaced by the given character. This allows to include special
     characters like : %, $, \\

   Any $PRINT specification before a $PRINTFMT specification will be
ignored.


@EndNode

@Node "Alias" "AFileEnglish.guide/Alias"
@Next "AREXX"
@Prev "PrintFmtSpec"
@Toc "Main"

Aliases
*******

   Aliases allow you to make data entering easier, by defining
shortcuts. An example is the possibility to enter "?" in a DATE field,
in order to have today's date. This possibility is built in AFile, but
you can also define your own aliases, using a text file made of lines
containing:

  1. the field's name

  2. the alias value

  3. the corresponding value

   Here is an example:

     ;Field  Alias   Value
     COUNTRY FRG     FEDERAL REPUBLIC OF GERMANY
     COUNTRY USA     UNITED STATES OF AMERICA
     COUNTRY UK      UNITED KINGDOM

   With this example, each time the user will enter the "USA" value in
the "COUNTRY" field, this value will automatically be replaced by the
"UNITED STATES OF AMERICA" string. Take care that aliases substitution
is performed before running an eventual verification AREXX script (see
@{"Input masks" Link "InputMask"}).

   The aliases file's name must be equal to the name of the data file,
followed by the @{b}.alias@{ub} suffix. For example, if you want to define
aliases for a data file named @{b}Addresses@{ub}, the aliases file's name must
be @{b}Addresses.alias@{ub}. The two files must be in the same directory. The
aliases file will automatically be opened when the data file is opened.


@EndNode

@Node "AREXX" "AFileEnglish.guide/AREXX"
@Next "History"
@Prev "Alias"
@Toc "Main"

AREXX Interface
***************

   AFile has a full AREXX interface, so AREXX may be considered as
AFile's programming language. The name of the AREXX port is @{b}AFile_rexx@{ub}.
You can run a script using the @{i}Execute AREXX@{ui} menu item, from the
@{i}Special@{ui} menu of the data access window. In this case, the current
file is automatically selected as the working file, and the current
record in this file is the record currently displayed.

   The following commands are accepted:

@{i}OPEN name@{ui}
     Opens the given file, and go to the first record of this file

     This file is @{i}NOT@{ui} selected as the working file.

@{i}SELECT name@{ui}
     Selects the given file as the working file. This file must have
     been opened using the @{i}OPEN@{ui} command.

@{i}CLOSE name@{ui}
     Closes the given file.

@{i}CLOSE ALL@{ui}
     Closes any opened file.

   The following commands are applied to the working file:

@{i}INFO@{ui}
     Returns informations about the current file, in the RESULT
     variable:

     "full pathname" <number of fields> <record size> <number of
     available records> <number of deleted records>.

@{i}FIELDLIST@{ui}
     Returns the list of the field's names of the file, in the RESULT
     variable. Field's names are separated by a space.

@{i}FIELDTYPE name@{ui}
     Returns the type of the field named "name" ("A", "N", "S", "D" or
     "B"), in the RESULT variable

@{i}FIELDLEN name@{ui}
     Returns the length of the field named "name", as declared in
     file's structure definition, in the RESULT variable. For numeric
     fields, the decimal point is taken in account if the number of
     digits is not zero.

@{i}ENUMLIST name@{ui}
     Returns the list of the possible values for the ENUM field named
     "name", in the RESULT variable. The values are separated by a
     comma.

@{i}CURRENTPOS@{ui}
     Returns the number of the current record, in the RESULT variable.

@{i}APPEND@{ui}
     Appends a new record, and moves to this record.

@{i}SEEK FIRST@{ui}
     Moves the first record.

@{i}SEEK LAST@{ui}
     Moves the last record.

@{i}SEEK NEXT@{ui}
     Moves the next record.

@{i}SEEK PREV@{ui}
     Moves the previous record.

@{i}SEEK n@{ui}
     Moves the n-th record.

@{i}SEARCH name value [NOCASE] [EXACT] [{=|<>|<|<=|>|>=}]@{ui}
     Searches a record which field named "name" contains the "value"
     value. If the "NOCASE" option is specified, the search will be
     case independant. If the "EXACT" option is specified, AFile will
     search a field equal to the value. The last option allow to
     specify the comparison to perform (equality is the default).

@{i}SEARCH NEXT@{ui}
     Searches next occurence.

@{i}SORT name [DECREASE] [NOCASE]@{ui}
     Adds the given field as a new sort key. If the "DECREASE" option
     is specified, the records will be sorted in reverse order. If the
     "NOCASE" option is specified, the sort will be case independant.

@{i}RELEASE {LAST|ALL}@{ui}
     Removes the last, or all sort keys.

@{i}REORDER@{ui}
     Reorders the file, and removes all sort keys.

@{i}PACK@{ui}
     Removes all "deleted" tagged records.

@{i}UNDELETE@{ui}
     Clears all the "deleted" tags on records.

   The following commands are applied to the current record of the
working file:

@{i}WRITE@{ui}
     Updates the current record.

@{i}DELETE@{ui}
     Deletes the current record.

@{i}GETFIELD name@{ui}
     Returns the value of the field named "name", in the RESULT
     variable.

@{i}SETFIELD name value@{ui}
     Modifies the value of the field named "name" to "value". @{i}Caution,
     the value must be specified within double quotes !@{ui}. Alias
     substitution is performed, and the eventual verification script is
     called.

   If failed, all these commands return 10 in the RC variable. They
return 0 if all is ok.

   The PACK and REORDER commands may return 20 as a return code, which
means a fatal error has occured. In this case, AFile execution is
immediatly terminated.


@EndNode

@Node "History" "AFileEnglish.guide/History"
@Prev "AREXX"
@Toc "Main"

History
*******

   AFile is written in C language, and was developped on an Amiga 3000
(25 Mhz processors, 10 Mb RAM, internal HD disk drive, 160 Mb internal
hard disk, external SyQuest drive of 88 Mb, external CD-ROM drive and
Star LC24-10 printer) running under 3.1 OS release.

@{i}v1.00, 25-Jul-93, 60448 bytes@{ui}
     First released version.

@{i}v1.10, 07-Aug-93, 62632 bytes@{ui}
     Added input masks.

     Added AREXX commands "FIELDTYPE" and "FIELDLEN".

     When a sort is activated, displays "sorted on <field's name>" in
     the status line (instead of just "sorted").

@{i}v1.20, 06-Sep-93, 64336 bytes@{ui}
     The number of fields is no longer limited.

     Sorting modified: field selection with a request box, added "lwr =
     UPR" option, AREXX interface enhanced.

     You can select the file to import/export with a file requester.

@{i}v1.21, 12-Sep-93, 64500 bytes@{ui}
     Uses new versions of OuvreEcran(), RequeteFic() and
     GetDefaultTextFont() functions.

@{i}v1.30, 15-Sep-93, 65612 bytes@{ui}
     Localized.

@{i}v1.31, 07-Oct-93, 65704 bytes@{ui}
     When an AREXX script is finished, waits for the user to press
     RETURN before closing the output window.

     Bug fixed: sorting numeric fields was made on the inverse order
     than asked.

@{i}v1.40, 14-Oct-93, 67036 bytes@{ui}
     You can modify the structure of an existing file.

     Added aliases.

     Reports errors occuring when loading input masks and aliases.

     Bug fixed in string requests handling.

     Some source cleanup.

@{i}v1.41, 17-Nov-93, 67292 bytes@{ui}
     Update the file header each time a record is added/deleted
     (instead of waiting for the file to be closed).

     A few enhancements in source files.

     When a request is displayed, locks main window with a Requester.

     Bug fixed in refresh of gadget associated with boolean fields.

     A few changes in order to support german catalogue.

@{i}v2.00, 28-Nov-93, 68960 bytes@{ui}
     You can now encrypt data in your files.

     Added "PRINTSCRIPT" argument.

     Bug fixed in fast copy of data fields: ln_Pred of first field, and
     ln_Succ of last field, were not updated.

@{i}v2.10, 11-Dec-93, 69508 bytes@{ui}
     Changed input mask files format: there is now a single file (the
     AREXX script) which both specifies messages and performs
     verifications. The old input mask files are still recognized.

     You may have an input mask file be automatically loaded when a
     data file is open.

     Status and gadgets lines are now just below the last field's
     gadget, instead of beeing at the bottom of the screen.

     When creating/changing a file's structure, changing a field's type
     no longer modifies the field's length when the new type is "DATE"
     or "BOOLEAN".

@{i}v2.20, 25-Dec-93, 70876 bytes@{ui}
     Extended input masks: custom menu with $MENU, print script
     selection with $PRINT.

     Compiled with SAS/C 6.50.

@{i}v2.21, 26-Jan-94, 70876 bytes@{ui}
     Bug fixed: didn't restore default public screen after running an
     AREXX script.

     Shows my new address.

@{i}v2.30, 20-Feb-94, 71412 bytes@{ui}
     Handles keyboard : arrow keys (+ shift), "p", "g", "DEL".

     Added USEASL argument.

     In an input mask, a line beginning with " **" is a comment.

     Default number of records to print is set to one.

     The field requester has now a blue background.

     Compiled with SAS/C 6.51.

@{i}v3.00, 26-Feb-94, 74696 bytes@{ui}
     Added $MASK specification (full mask with background picture and
     field positionning).

     Added DEPTH argument.

     Enhanced internal file requester.

     Enhanced error handling (now displays some messages...).

     Documentation formatted by TexInfo/MakeGuide.

@{i}v3.01, 05-Mar-94, 74732 bytes@{ui}
     Bug fixed: displayed an error message when opening a file without
     corresponding @{b}.mask@{ub} file.

     Restores palette when a file is closed.

@{i}v3.02, 25-Mar-94, 75088 bytes@{ui}
     Bug fixed: used a @{b}graphics.library@{ub} V39 function (so worked only
     under OS 3.1).

     Bug fixed in AREXX message handling (some commands were refused)

     Bug fixed: sending arguments to the verification AREXX script was
     not good.

     Displays type and size of the current field, on the status line

@{i}v3.10, 06-Apr-94, 78960 bytes@{ui}
     Added new field type "ENUM"

     Rewritten search fonction : now opens a window for search options,
     added "exact match" and "not equal" options

     Added "FONT" argument

     "ALPHA" type fields now only accept lowercase and upercase letters
     (with or without accents), space, dash and single quote

     Displays current field's type and size in the status line

     Adds the pathname of the current data file if a script file name
     has no path in an input mask

     With full input masks ($MASK specification), displays status lines
     and action gadgets in the bottom of the screen

     Enhanced field request : if a data is missing when
     adding/inserting/replacing a field, the corresponding gadget is
     automatically activated

     Several bug fixed (was eating memory, problems with loading of
     input masks, ...)

@{i}v3.11, 16-Apr-94, 79220 bytes@{ui}
     Added "NOCASE" argument

     Some source cleanup/reorganization (data access interface)

     Locks input for structure definition window when the file
     requester is displayed ("Copy structure" item)

     Removed fast field definitions copy (can't be done in a "system
     friendly" way, generated memory corruption)

     Bug fixed in CLI argument parsing

@{i}v3.12, 21-May-94, 79220 bytes@{ui}
     The data access Intuition interface now handles century in dates

     Bug fixed : "TOOL TYPES" were not scanned the good way

@{i}v3.13, 05-Jul-94, 79684 bytes@{ui}
     Added the AREXXWIN argument

     The name of the public screen is "AFile"

     A few bugs fixed in IFF pictures loading

@{i}v3.20, 27-Jul-94, 80368 bytes@{ui}
     Modified input masks format (added $PRINTFMT specification,
     CHECK/ARGS/QUIET keywords)

     Added "Close and quit" item in "File" menu

     Bug fixed: sometimes didn't redraw gadget bar

     Bug fixed: after sorting or packing, if you select "forget mask"
     the display was not good, and "select mask" made the system crash

     Bug fixed: a lonely $PRINT specification in an input mask was
     ignored

@{i}v3.30, 25-Sep-94, 81060 bytes@{ui}
     The files may now be sorted on several keys

@{i}v4.00, 11-Feb-95, 69788 octets@{ui}
     Brand new GUI, using the @{b}gadtools.library@{ub}.

     Added PUBSCREEN, SCREENMODE and DISPLAYID arguments.

     You can now search a value lower or greater.

     Import/Export options may now be saved and loaded.

@{i}v4.01, 28-Feb-95, 69936 bytes@{ui}
     With Kickstart V39 or greater, uses "Memory Pools" in order to
     minimize memory fragmentation

     A few errors corrected in value searching

@{i}v4.02, 07-May-95, 70688 bytes@{ui}
     When modifying a file structure, you can now change the field type
     (this fixes the problem with new fields type specification).

     Bug fixed in font opening (couldn't load fonts from FONTS:)

@{i}v4.03, 21-May-95, 70812 bytes@{ui}
     Bug fixed in import/export request (crashed the Amiga under
     Kickstart V39+)

     If the modification of a field fails, put back the previous value
     and re-activate the gadget

     Correctly update the status lines when a string gadget is selected
     with the mouse, or validated with TAB/Shift-TAB

     Searching with the "Exact match" option disabled didn't worked

@{i}v4.10, 27-May-95, 71036 bytes@{ui}
     Added AREXX commands "FIELDLIST", "PACK", "UNDELETE" and "REORDER"

     Bug fixed in input masks : fields where all located at (0,0) if
     the $MSG specification was used.

     Bug fixed in input masks : the window was not always totally
     cleared when switching on/off the input mask.

     Bug fixed in sort : a sort started from AREXX couldn't be removed
     from the GUI.

     Bug fixed in files handling : the current file could be closed
     from an AREXX script.

@{i}v4.11, 10-Jun-95, 72240 bytes@{ui}
     Allows spaces in $MENU specifications (and not only tabs)

     Allows RETURN/ESCAPE keys for all requests

     Added "CURRENTPOS" command

     Locks the current window during all "long" operations (sort,
     search, ...)

     With Kickstart V39+, sets the busy mouse pointer when the window
     is locked

     Bug fixed in interface : "Remove sort key/All" did "Remove sort
     key/Last" (and inv.)

     Bug fixed in sorting : could crash the program by a stack overflow
     (now uses __stackext)

     Bug fixed in AREXX : if you did a "SETFIELD" for a field with
     verification (CHECK in mask), the final field's value was wrong

@{i}v4.12, 02-Jul-95, 72428 bytes@{ui}
     A few bugs fixed in searching functions

     Bug fixed in AREXX : SETFIELD didn't allow "?" as a shorcut for
     today's date

     Bug fixed in interface : since v4.11, didn't react to the "Ok" and
     "Cancel" gadgets on the Import/Export window

     Bug fixed in input masks : the message is no longer truncated at
     the first space or tabulation in $MSG and $MASK specifications

@{i}v4.13, 29-Jul-95, 72608 bytes@{ui}
     The number request may now also be used with the keyboard

     Bug fixed : the PACK command could use another file that the
     current one

@{i}4.14, 01-Jan-98, 72508 bytes@{ui}
     Bug fixed : a click over an ENUM fields updated to field value
     twice

     Bug fixed : when the default display used more than one page, and
     an input mask was used, some fields gadgets were not correctly
     updated

     Compiled with SAS/C 6.57

@{i}4.15, 05-Jan-98, 72927 bytes@{ui}
     Added confirmation requests when deleting or creating records

     Bug fixed : data encryption didn't worked (the file was just made
     unusuable :-)

     Bug fixed : when a wrong password was given at the opening of a
     encrypted file, the main menu remainded locked

     Bug fixed : when exiting from "structure modification", the file
     was not always closed

     Bug fixed : when asking a "structure modification" on an encrypted
     file, the "Encrypt data" item in the "Options" menu was not
     activated

     Bug fixed : used the total screen size instead of the visible
     screen size

     Bug fixed : when an input mask had a picture, didn't restore the
     screen colors when closing the input mask

@EndNode

